  <para>
    Defining a &field; on a &mesh; means that the &field; has values
    that can be computed on the &mesh;: memory is allocated to store
    the components of the &field; at the <link
      linkend="Section-Concepts-Mesh-Geometry">nodes</link> of the
    &mesh;, and values can be interpolated within the &mesh; elements.
  </para>
  <para>
    When a &field; is first defined, its components are all zero
    everywhere.  To assign &field; values, use <xref
    linkend="MenuItem-OOF.Mesh.Set_Field_Initializer"/> and <xref
    linkend="MenuItem-OOF.Mesh.Apply_Field_Initializers"/>.  To solve
    for &field; values, the &field; must be <link
    linkend="MenuItem-OOF.Subproblem.Field.Activate">activated</link>,
    an &equation; involving the &field; must be <link
    linkend="MenuItem-OOF.Subproblem.Equation.Activate">activated</link>,
    and the &mesh; must be <link
    linkend="MenuItem-OOF.Mesh.Solve">solved</link>.
  </para>



